{"sequence":60,"timestamp":"2026-04-15T14:33:08.650151791Z","event_type":"amendment_queued","details":{"amendment_id":"fr-3-db6d9c9f","body":"finding_summary: `milestone show`, `milestone status`, and `milestone plan` surface raw snapshot-read failures without the milestone id. `load_milestone_summary` and `load_milestone_detail` call `load_snapshot` directly at `src/cli/milestone.rs:337` and `src/cli/milestone.rs:365`, and `load_or_start_milestone_requirements_run` does the same at `src/cli/milestone.rs:523`. If `status.json` is missing or unreadable, the CLI exits with a bare `No such file or directory (os error 2)` instead of the required milestone-specific message; I reproduced this by creating a milestone directory without `status.json` and running `milestone show ms-alpha`.\nseverity: medium\naffected_files:\n- src/cli/milestone.rs\nremediation_hint: Wrap snapshot-load failures in `AppError::MilestoneOperationFailed { milestone_id, action, details }` for show/status/plan, the same way plan inspection errors are normalized.","dedup_key":"e998a573ff93eb035dbd8dbbcac678cbd346a7f12c356f9e4928bcd2c87d2681","reviewer_sources":[{"backend_family":"codex","model_id":"gpt-5.4-xhigh","reviewer_id":"reviewer-1"}],"run_id":"run-20260415130611","source":"workflow_stage","source_stage":"final_review"}}
{"sequence":61,"timestamp":"2026-04-15T14:33:08.659592482Z","event_type":"amendment_queued","details":{"amendment_id":"fr-3-a5330ad4","body":"finding_summary: `milestone plan` performs a check-then-start-then-record sequence for `pending_requirements_run_id` without a single milestone-scoped critical section. `load_or_start_milestone_requirements_run` reads the snapshot at `src/cli/milestone.rs:523-536`, starts a new long-running requirements flow at `src/cli/milestone.rs:538-548`, and only then persists the pending run at `src/cli/milestone.rs:549` / `src/cli/milestone.rs:584-597`. Two concurrent `milestone plan <id>` invocations can therefore both observe `None`, launch separate requirements runs, and race to materialize different bundles; the earlier command can even report success while the later command overwrites the plan and clears a different pending id.\nseverity: high\naffected_files:\n- src/cli/milestone.rs\nremediation_hint: Reserve the planning slot under `with_milestone_write_lock` before launching the requirements pipeline, or add a compare-and-set/in-progress marker so only one requirements run can exist per milestone.","dedup_key":"845cac4b43bc12439d4188b99053dbe965b091fc1165a5575d7e98fde4a88cad","reviewer_sources":[{"backend_family":"codex","model_id":"gpt-5.4-xhigh","reviewer_id":"reviewer-1"}],"run_id":"run-20260415130611","source":"workflow_stage","source_stage":"final_review"}}
{"sequence":62,"timestamp":"2026-04-15T14:33:08.668876889Z","event_type":"amendment_queued","details":{"amendment_id":"fr-3-8988fcf3","body":"finding_summary: `milestone show`/`status` can falsely report `plan metadata is stale` during a normal replan because the new reader treats any plan-hash mismatch as corruption at `src/cli/milestone.rs:426-434`, but plan artifacts are written before the snapshot hash/version is committed in `src/contexts/milestone_record/service.rs:1648-1662`. A concurrent read can therefore observe the new `plan.json` together with the old `status.json` and fail even though the write is still in progress.\nseverity: medium\naffected_files:\n- src/cli/milestone.rs\n- src/contexts/milestone_record/service.rs\nremediation_hint: Publish plan artifacts and snapshot metadata atomically, or teach readers to detect/tolerate the in-flight milestone write instead of treating the transient mismatch as corruption.","dedup_key":"27ae7e5c51956cfc28163537e94470ac13bdce19ac4551013e662a2be544a10a","reviewer_sources":[{"backend_family":"codex","model_id":"gpt-5.4-xhigh","reviewer_id":"reviewer-1"}],"run_id":"run-20260415130611","source":"workflow_stage","source_stage":"final_review"}}
